The diet of an obese child: do not take breakfast and take the charcuterie for dinner
Over one third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren weigh above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families who have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the patterns around him is.
For example, on the tables of obese children, 50 per cent of the carcuterie is found more often than in normal-weight children's families.
19% of the obese had frites at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness action "obesity is not a chance"
In the families of the big kids sport is also not a habit, which is now the case of most of today's schoolchildren - only 15% answered that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and 900 students from primary schools in Czech Republic participated.
This was the second edition of "obesity is not a chance", supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever Society.
From the beginning, more than 12000 students from sixth to third enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight, or even obese children, is the absence, proper eating and not enough physical exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned for example indicate eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch-dining- dinner, which is the basic principle of a good diet," indicates one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and dinner charcuterie
Specialists draw attention to the fact that for healthy development it takes some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In Czech Republic, only 23% of students' families eat at the same time.
In most families everyone has their own breakfast.
And the worst thing that's been raised is that one tenth of the population doesn't have breakfast at all.
Even so, breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy frits are more often consumed in obese children's families.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks every day sweet drinks (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned regularly do sports, but for parents it is only half, 15%.
Prepare your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet from the possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children from 12 to 15 years of age are far from ideal in terms of a healthy diet."
Among their favourite dishes there are many cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is, in particular, a great preference for sweet lemonades," is indicated in the survey results.
For lunch are the pastas that took the first place just in front of the white meat.
The children did not want any starch, and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Health Check
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive ad hoc information.
"In the course of a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session "obesity is not a chance," a determined determination was made to go to a healthy diet," indicates the results of the survey.
For example, the most striking was for sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children have most often checked white meat and fish as their main dish on the questionnaire and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread and potato pellets).
