How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, because the trips to the west were very limited.
The Czech tourists were travelling for vacations in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a inclination for the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (so for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency agreement that was the condition to travel west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not at all travel.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the agreement of currencies (Western Currency) to travel west.
The Czechs mostly spent their vacations in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs were buying and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989 the Czechs' journeys have been undergoing a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the holiday in East Germany and Bulgaria was at most,the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad last year in the countries of the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the West caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for long travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, the travel organizations had Czechs sleeping in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical trait of a journey from Czechs was at this time to take away its own food cans, sausages, etc. to save.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades of free purchasing of Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased what has caused around 1997 another important moment.
As a result of a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started preparing tours with air charter links since 1997, which have considerably reduced costs in comparison with the previous ones.
By the end of the 1990s the Czechs had visa-free links with almost most developed countries around the world, except for the EU that later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
It is more than 100,000 Czechs who visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to completely line up in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for vacations abroad including related expenses.
