Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which delivers the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book that he described, accurately, as "a book of anti-history."
It has some known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and material.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, that a "book describing what it might look like." We find there "feeling, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolchildren and botanists to climbers, passing by doctors, ambulancemen and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose members, become mad or lose their lives.
Their lives vacillate here like the candles of a church: while some of them die out, there are new ones.
Peter Englund's book differs from traditional history books.
It brings a disdain to the idea that the First World War is only summed up by the terrible war of the trenches on the western front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skilfully describes other war theatres: the Alps, the Balkans, the eastern front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; a Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsetse flies are an unattainable problem.
