According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been expanded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memories, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or passionate, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
