The liars look you in the eyes.
They don't beat, roar, or shake.
Not to conclude that mentors are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the facial micro-expressions, the formation of the question and the time of response.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
The good mentors are able to read the others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "centered on them" while women say more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - than married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call establishing the benchmarks.
This helps to provide a reference point to measure subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, and vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally stirs his feet constantly so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him stir his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for hints of verbal and non-verbal deceptions.
