Climate adversity slowed the economy
In the first year of managing Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, called for change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
Low temperatures in February, apart from the losses of billions for the agricultural sector, have limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, have caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historical fall of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of allocations by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there have been damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent have suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 per cent have suffered partial damage, the main crops affected have been vegetables, corn and chican peas.
The decline in economic activity has led to a steady rise in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, in the first three quarters of the year an accelerated increase has been observed, as during the period from January to March 55,053 signalees were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average has continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand unemployed signals, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to earn, to invest and use them in something," he says.
Migration in detention
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been limited, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because they already have a lot of difficulties to find work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the signaoen labour market worsens by considering the high level of the lack of serious ones that prevails between the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for the shift to the state is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7,000 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 the largest reduction in the Foreign Direct Investment over the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Secretary of Economy from January to June, the State FDI has reached $630 thousand,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5 million,143 thousand,312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos a year, registered mainly by the tertiary companies.
Debt
Given the economic contraction scenario, in July the Government of the State requested the approval of a 3 billion pesos loan for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 billion pesos and until November no benefit of debt was observed in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For employers' representatives, Mario López Valdés' first year of government demonstrates a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Industry of Transformation, said that in 2011 there was no harmonisation of the wills of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year has been really poor, it is necessary to work hard to recover the terrain that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have had to align the effort of all and especially the already synchronized good progress of this new team of government, hopefully next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as early-year ice cream retained the economy of the state and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flux is produced from several events, including frosts, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level and flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confédération Patronale de la República Mexicane de Sinaloa, said that it is intended to channel the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources be realized," he says.
A lot to do
The President of Copromex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to achieve good results in various areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the way in which public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked hard and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do," he says.
