The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional disputes that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies formulated against the presidential decree that advanced the so-called "analogue coupure" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it were not met.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to bring about the transition to digital terrestrial television.
