The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and jeopardized the whole of the Eurozone.
A communiqué from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in its majority by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the result of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "framework is now well drawn", he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to levels impossible to support.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy that had been affected.
