MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Insurance conducts an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people, called 'Genetics of obesity of children and adolescents' protocol that will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialities Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation is invited to participate in the population with or without the right to attend the sporting units participating in the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is provided to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (State of Mexico East).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (southern Federal District) and finally in the Sportsive Morelos Unit (northern Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that is to understand the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he said that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years old, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It has detailed that the Saturdays will apply to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, and insulin and genetics (the people associated with childhood obesity are being identified).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there has been an increase of 77 per cent in obesity for boys and 47 per cent for girls; with regard to overweight, there has also been a dramatic increase', said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search of markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of Indo-American heredity, 30 per cent of Europe and 5 per cent of Africa, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that is consumed (calorie), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full assessment of children, which allows them to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-coloured folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the probability of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetic alterations.
The information is handled in a confidential way, and doctors write it to parents, each of which explains the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to perform to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay mostly the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking in short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - cornmeal pulp wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better efficiency, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signals were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Métropolitaine area of Valle de México, averted Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous paving is adequate, the cases could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his lecture A technological opinion on cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory to which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both to highs and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this modified type of asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the performance, and thus the formation of the cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has a almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, it adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that most of the streets of Mexico City were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, he pointed out, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If asphalt had been modified, it would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt layer, he said, we put a final layer called bearing layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer is in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the bearing layer also requires that the floor has an adequate thickness and the material it is made of must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, as they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to do, which softens all layers of the floor and therefore causes the cassis.
In the process of forming a cassis, he said, the first to be damaged is the rolling film and only subsequently is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Investigators System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the paving should always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid the frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, the bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair the cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
