Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A PCD from Cali has gone into history like the man who has confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4th, a CTI dactyloscopicist from Cali passed on to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven dactyloscopicists working in the local offices of the ITC, this week it was the "availability" tour of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to reach the place where the corpses were to be identified.
The year 2000 was transferred to the capital of Valle and after following appropriate courses, he specialized in dactylloscopy, which is the study of the skin of friction, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar had been warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter in Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be one of the man who was leading the world's oldest guerilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical aspect, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonic magnifying glass, ink, picker and lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye was not mistaken: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the one who confirmed to the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
Searching for the fingerprint
For a dactyloscopicist from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos has made in Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, with no margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from identifying the corpses, dactyloscopicists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher stated that in a case of robbery he had to remove a part of a wall from a house, because in this place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to get the full handprint and identify the offender who had participated in various flights," he recalls.
The fingerprints may also remove or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent could be suspected of the crime and indeed a mark on the bottle coincided.
Even if this does not guarantee that he is the killer, it places him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscopicist explained that "digital fingerprints of objects are extracted with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a picker or strip is used to pick them up.
Later, the fingerprints were sent to Asif, the database of the declinquents, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
He explained that everything is not as shown in the CSI television program.
Like everything that shines isn't gold, all that we touch doesn't necessarily become a footprint.
It can, however, be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
