Japan was reborn after the earthquake
GDP rose by 1.5% due to domestic consumption and ended the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralysed, convalescent even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in Japan since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo calculated material losses at $300,000, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
The second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
Recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by earthquake and tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared with a decrease of 0.9% in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of unbroken increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites you to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructures, use the deficiencies to believe in zero.
Japan has mostly awakened thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
