We need to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says an expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to speak to their doctors about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
It is one of the conclusions of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, with six experts involved in various areas, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code in such a way as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
The experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the planet.
If Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has led to a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death."
Medalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, reporting to us experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die in the hospital.
Overall, it is in Quebec that this rate is highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code concerning euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuses in application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide in non-competent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, the co-signator of the report, there would be more cases of these spills in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
It should be recalled that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out for euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of the elderly or the disabled are less valuable.
As for those who practise assisted suicide, respondents estimate that 41% should not be prosecuted.
