The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised in various ways - aggravation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the number policy, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France's "human rights countries".
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the passage that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analysed in the economic angle.
There is quite a broad consensus between the left and the right on this subject.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, fear of invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be harmed towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande is singing banality, saying that co-development will help solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electoral pay; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book that synthesizes the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants are likely to replace national workers, particularly those with low qualifications, with downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, most of whom are trades in sectors where there is a shortage of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A Positive Impact on Wages
In the same way as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that an increase of 1% of migratory flows results in an increase between 0.6% and 0.9% of real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (the high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo have been founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant reaching the age of 30 will make a net contribution (receiving less expenditure) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average throughout his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the term, to go looking for the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
