North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia by passing through the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with flash.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the Baltic shores last Tuesday, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the opening of the North Stream, this new pipeline that connects directly under the sea Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, the Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, the French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte shot together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the west-European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube connecting the region of Saint Petersburg to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012 to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and in time of this huge building has a victory air.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut down access to western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security from its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of the energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has managed to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are highly gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us in an organic way," said François Fillon in inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how political as well as economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-plated steel to protect it against the anchors of ships.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred must have been removed or destroyed by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts throughout its length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but the project leaders resigned while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state corporation settle permanently off their coasts.
"In case of failure, we stop passing the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline is therefore released into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders who planned the welds to get a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the status of the gas pipeline shall be carried out by an underwater robot, drawn by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus operating inside the gas pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, wide of one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, he provides accurate information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate 50 years without having to undergo any repair.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars from the start, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for twenty years renewable, all the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both tubes.
For example, for GDF Suez, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, as only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a trademark.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskin wants to restore the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine Carnet is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine Carnet as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode Mode, based in Milan, decides at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (tope skin), which means a varnished cotton used to cover banquets for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has restored to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has become responsible for the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces.
It is far from confidential production in the early years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It's difficult to establish a buyer's portrait, because the notebook seduces both businessman and student and professionals.
In Moleskine's image, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, counts almost 100 today and has since 2008 two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in the bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shopping malls and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the increase of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition " Detour " where architects or artists display their own books.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Using its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand is based on a wide range of media.
A success that has made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Synthegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is even higher than the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the general population.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adaptive, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled."
" Progress over the past 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
" There remains, however, a great deal to be done. "
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before they have access to employment.
Rather, they are older: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria which only complicate the return to employment, and which "constitute the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses recruit workers with disabilities.
That's for objective brakes.
There remains the non-word, the mentality that evolves, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City indicated that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of 1987.
The latest known figures, dated 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
" But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments from 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises from 100 to 199 employees.
